transcript: I am back, once again showcasing some of the craziest and most rare shoes in the entire world and today I got one that I absolutely love and finally can't wait to show you guys. I've honestly had these shoes for a very long time, and crazy enough these actually come from one of the most popular heavy metal bands of all time. Rumored only 24 pairs worldwide, 200 million units sold across the world, and being one of the most popular heavy metal bands of all time, we have the Iron Maiden SB Dunk High and oh my god. Even these, being over two decades old, they are still brand new to this day, and that is absolutely insane. And as I mentioned earlier, only 24 pairs in the entire world exist only given to the friends and family members of the Iron Maiden band. With that many pairs existing in the entire world, who knows how many left are still brand new. These are probably one of, if not, the rarest Nike SB Dunk to exist. Now to start off with the details on this shoe, you have a very premium shiny black leather with a very gorgeous, beautiful dark suede to follow along. And then on the back of the right heel, you have "Maiden" and on the back of the left heel, you have "Iron," obviously referring to Iron Maiden. A cool detail that we never see Nike do is a clear swoosh. Now, obviously you could see it, for being a 22 year old shoe it has yellowed, but actually on this side, it is still kind of somewhat clear. Of course, the sickest detail of them all, you have Eddie right here on the side panel with some nice background. And, for those that don't know who Eddie is, he's basically Iron Maiden's mascot. He was all over their albums and certain singles and a bunch of famous vintage tees that now also go for thousands of dollars. And of course, you have it on the left shoe as well, slightly different background, but still same character. And right here on the right insole, you have Eddie, of course. But the left insole is actually pretty cool and has some deep significance to the fans. Now the "scream for me Long Beach" dates all the way back to 1985 during the World Slavery Tour that they had in Long Beach, California. The band was screaming into the mic, "Scream for me Long Beach." And obviously that was their way of saying "We love you Long Beach." And the crowd went absolutely crazy and that moment was so significant that during the year of that whole tour they dropped an album and this slogan made it on there many times. And other than coming with the box and some red laces, there's nothing else that goes with this shoe and crazy enough they are currently fetching anywhere between $25 to $35,000 depending on the size or if you can even find one. But do you think it's worth it? <noise>

transcript: These marketing geniuses, as they eventually became, were kind of flogging some imports out the back of that car, track meet as a side hustle, and didn't have a great grip on branding. You know, had one of the world's most recognizable symbols in their hands, weren't sure about it. You know, later had "Just Do It", obviously, which remains advertising executives' favorite ever slogan when they're voting for what's the best campaign of all time. Air Jordan's still to come and that association with sports stars. But at this point, even though they had the waffle shoe, the patent number 3,793,750, they didn't call it the Waffle Shoe for like another three years. They went to the 1972 United States Olympic Trials in Eugene the following year and called it the Moon Shoe. And the reason for that was it kind of made an impression in the sand and the dirt which looked a bit like Neil Armstrong's footprint. But again, like they had waffle shoe right there, but it still took a while for people to be like, "That's the Waffle Shoe that we're selling." Not the Moon Shoe.
